 OF COOL USTADZ: PREACHING, SUBCULTURES AND THE PEMUDA HIJRAH MOVEMENT -- t14 NEW RELIGIOUS PREACHER IN THE CHANGING RELIGIOUS AUTHORITY: THE OFFLINE AND ONLINE PREACHER OF USTADZ ABDUL SOMAD -- t15 SANTRI, CINEMA AND THE EXPLORATORY FORM OF AUTHORITY IN TRADITIONALIST MUSLIM INDONESIA -- t16 THE POLITICS OF RELIGIOUS AND CULTURAL AUTHORITY: CONTESTATION AND CO-EXISTENCE OF SULTANATE AND ISLAMIC MOVEMENTS IN THE POST-SUHARTO YOGYAKARTA AND TERNATE -- t17 JIHAD AGAINST THE GHAZWUL FIKRI: ACTORS AND MOBILIZATION STRATEGIES OF THE ISLAMIC UNDERGROUND MOVEMENT -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJust like the Gutenberg revolution in the fifteenth century, which led to the emergence of non-conventional religious authority in the Christian world, the current information technology revolution, particularly through mediums such as Facebook, Instagram, YouTube, and Twitter, has triggered the re-construction and decentralization of religious authority in Islam. New santri (pious individuals) and preachers emerged from the non-conventional religious educational system. They not only challenged the traditional authorities, but also redefine and re-conceptualize old religious terminologies, such as hijra and wasatiyya. This book explores the dynamics of religious authority in Indonesia with special attention to the challenges from the “new santri”. It is a rich and important book on religion. I recommend students of religion in Indonesia and other countries to read it. Ahmad Syafi’i Maarif Professor Emeritus of History at Yogyakarta State University An important and timely volume that addresses the changing nature of Islamic leadership in the world’s most popular Muslim country. This book debunks many (mis)perceptions that Indonesia Islam is monolithic. It also redefines dominant characterization of Islam by Orientalist scholars, such as santri and abangan Muslims. Haedar Nashir Chairman of Muhammadiyah This edited volume evaluates the new development of Islamic scholarship and authority in Indonesia. Things have changed significantly in recent times that make many observers and researchers wondering: has Indonesia moved from traditional authorities, mainstream Islamic organizations, and the established scholarship to the new actors, movements and platforms? Has the change occurs owing to the democratization and political reforms that took place in the last twenty years or are there other factors we need to take into account? The contributors in this book provide possible answers from many different areas and perspectives. It’s a must-read! Nadirsyah Hosen Monash University, Australia  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aIslam and politicszIndonesia. 0aIslam and statezIndonesia. 0aIslamic religious educationzIndonesia. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Islamic Studies.2bisacsh1 aAbdullah, M. Amin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAfriko, Marzi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAkmaliah, Wahyudi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArrobi, Moh Zaki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAzca, M. Najib, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurhani, Ahmad Najib, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurhani, Ahmad Najib, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHamdani,, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasan, Noorhaidi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasyim, Syafiq, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuda, Ahmad Nuril, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 